# GA Gate Assignment: Performance Fixes

## What's slow and why

Profiled the code and found 5 spots burning most of the CPU. The GA runs 500+ generations on a large dataset — small inefficiencies per generation stack up fast.

---

### BN-1 — Sort calls calculateFitness twice per comparison (GeneticEngine.java ~L85)

```java
population.sort((c1, c2) -> Double.compare(
    evaluator.calculateFitness(c2, flights),
    evaluator.calculateFitness(c1, flights)));
```

With P=200 chromosomes, the sort makes ~1,530 comparisons per generation. Each one calls `calculateFitness` twice — that's 3,060 full O(N) passes over all flights just to sort. Fix: pre-compute a `double[] fitnessCache` once at the top of `evolve()`, then sort by index using the cached values.

---

### BN-2 — getBestSolution rescans the whole population after it's already sorted (GeneticEngine.java ~L286)

After `evolve()` finishes, the population is already sorted descending. Then `getBestSolution()` loops through it again calling `calculateFitness` P more times to find what's already at index 0. Should just return `population.get(0)`.

---

### BN-3 — new Random() on every single call (GeneticEngine.java ~L104, L122, L169)

`select()`, `crossover()`, and `mutate()` each construct a `new Random()` every time they're called. Besides the allocation overhead, back-to-back calls share seeds from `System.nanoTime()`, which quietly degrades the randomness. One shared `private final Random rand` field on the class is the fix.

---

### BN-4 — getValidGates walks all gates twice on every mutation (GeneticEngine.java ~L140)

Every call to `getValidGates(f, evaluator)` does two linear scans through the gate list. With P mutations per generation, that's O(P×G) work per generation just for mutation alone. Pre-building a `Map<PlaneType, Map<Boolean, List<Gate>>>` cache in the constructor cuts this to an O(1) lookup.

---

### BN-5 — getConflictIndices rebuilds the same gateMap on every conflict check (GeneticEngine.java ~L199)

```java
Map<Integer, Gate> gateMap = new HashMap<>();
for (Gate g : gates) gateMap.put(g.getId(), g);
```

This is rebuilt from scratch inside every `getConflictIndices()` call. It's the same map every time. Moving it to a private field initialized in the constructor fixes it — same pattern already used in `FitnessEvaluator`.

---

## What to change

All changes are in `GeneticEngine.java`:

- Add `private final Random rand` field (BN-3)
- Add `private Map<Integer, Gate> gateMap` field, built in constructor (BN-5)
- Add `private Map<PlaneType, Map<Boolean, List<Gate>>> validGatesCache`, built in constructor (BN-4)
- Refactor `evolve()` to pre-compute `double[] fitnessCache`, sort by it (BN-1)
- Simplify `getBestSolution()` to `return population.get(0)` (BN-2)
- Update `select()`, `crossover()`, `mutate()`, `getConflictIndices()` to use the shared fields instead of allocating new objects

---

## How to verify

Run `MassiveScaleTest` (500 flights, 200 pop, 500 gens) and check two things:
- Final fitness is the same or better — the algorithm itself hasn't changed, just the caching
- No NPE or out-of-bounds from the new maps

For a quick smoke test without the full dataset, `GeneticEngine.main` works fine. Wall-clock time should be noticeably faster, especially at higher generation counts.
